  "prompt": "What are movies that everyone should see?",
  "response": "Here\u2019s a curated list of movies that are widely considered essential viewing due to their cultural significance, storytelling, technical innovation, or influence on cinema. These films span genres and eras, offering something for everyone:\n\n### **Classics**\n1. **The Godfather** (1972) - A powerful saga of family, power, and loyalty.\n2. **Casablanca** (1942) - A timeless romance set against the backdrop of WWII.\n3. **Citizen Kane** (1941) - A groundbreaking exploration of ambition and media.\n4. **Gone with the Wind** (1939) - An epic tale of love and survival during the Civil War.\n5. **Schindler's List** (1993) - A harrowing yet beautiful story of human compassion during the Holocaust.\n\n### **Science Fiction**\n6. **2001: A Space Odyssey** (1968) - A visually stunning exploration of humanity and technology.\n7. **Blade Runner** (1982) - A philosophical and visually rich dive into identity and humanity.\n8. **Star Wars: Episode IV - A New Hope** (1977) - A space opera that redefined modern cinema.\n9. **The Matrix** (1999) - A mind-bending action film exploring reality and control.\n10. **Interstellar** (2014) - A visually stunning and emotional journey through space and time.\n\n### **Drama**\n11. **The Shawshank Redemption** (1994) - A moving story of hope and friendship.\n12. **Forrest Gump** (1994) - A heartwarming tale of an extraordinary life.\n13. **Pulp Fiction** (1994) - A non-linear masterpiece of crime and dark humor.\n14. **The Social Network** (2010) - A sharp exploration of ambition and betrayal.\n15. **12 Angry Men** (1957) - A gripping courtroom drama about justice and prejudice.\n\n### **Comedy**\n16. **Monty Python and the Holy Grail** (1975) - A hilarious and absurd take on Arthurian legend.\n17. **Some Like It Hot** (1959) - A classic screwball comedy with sharp wit.\n18. **Groundhog Day** (1993) - A clever exploration of life and self-improvement.\n19. **The Big Lebowski** (1998) - A quirky, cult-classic comedy about chaos and camaraderie.\n20. **Annie Hall** (1977) - A witty and heartfelt take on love and relationships.\n\n### **Animation**\n21. **Spirited Away** (2001) - A magical and emotional journey by Studio Ghibli.\n22. **Toy Story** (1995) - A groundbreaking and heartfelt story of friendship.\n23. **The Lion King** (1994) - A timeless tale of family, loss, and redemption.\n24. **Inside Out** (2015) - A creative and emotional exploration of human feelings.\n25. **Wall-E** (2008) - A touching and visually stunning story about love and environmentalism.\n\n### **Action**\n26. **Die Hard** (1988) - The quintessential action movie.\n27. **Mad Max: Fury Road** (2015) - A high-octane visual masterpiece.\n28. **The Dark Knight** (2008) - A dark and compelling take on the superhero genre.\n29. **Gladiator** (2000) - An epic tale of revenge and honor.\n30. **Inception** (2010) - A mind-bending heist film exploring dreams and reality.\n\n### **Horror**\n31. **The Exorcist** (1973) - A chilling exploration of faith and evil.\n32. **Psycho** (1960) - A groundbreaking psychological thriller.\n33. **Get Out** (2017) - A sharp and socially conscious horror film.\n34. **The Shining** (1980) - A haunting story of isolation and madness.\n35. **Alien** (1979) - A tense and groundbreaking sci-fi horror.\n\n### **International**\n36. **Parasite** (2019) - A darkly comedic exploration of class inequality.\n37. **Crouching Tiger, Hidden Dragon** (2000) - A visually stunning martial arts epic.\n38. **Life is Beautiful** (1997) - A heartwarming and heartbreaking story of love and resilience.\n39. **City of God** (2002) - A gritty and compelling look at life in the favelas of Rio.\n40. **Seven Samurai** (1954) - A masterpiece of storytelling and action.\n\nThis list is just a starting point\u2014there are countless other incredible films to explore! What\u2019s most important is finding movies that resonate with you personally.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
